Exit 6 of Jingfugong on Metro Line 3 is a park with communes built by Lee Chenggui in 1936 with the Royal Palace and the temple. The commune altar prays to the gods in charge of land and grain. Every October, a commune sacrifice is held.

In the Korean era, when the country suffered serious grain shortages, the park offered sacrifices and prayed for a good harvest. At the entrance of the social park, you will first meet the 177 National Treasure, the main entrance of the social altar. This gate is the first pass to enter the altar of social security, where the gods of land and grain are worshipped. The walls around the altar are square, with one gate in each of the four directions of northeast, southwest and northeast. Behind the altar is a shrine dedicated to Tanjun, the ancestor of the Korean nation, the first king of ancient Korea.
